scrolly-map.Copy: Before the invasion, Russian or Russian-supported forces controled Crimea and parts of Donetsk and Luhansk.
Two weeks into the war, Russian forces were just a handful of miles from the capital city Kyiv.
But a month later, this threat was reduced. Ukraine performed its first successful counteroffensive in the north of the country, when Russian forces were pushed away from Kyiv.
Since then, further counterattacks pushed the Russians away from the northern city of Kharkiv in September.

And then the regional capital of the illegally annexed oblast of Kherson in November. While much of the oblast's land is still in Russian hands, this was the only regional capital Russia has seized and was a big blow to lose it.
Now, one year on from the war, the two sides are locked in stalemate. Russian forces have once again made a few gains in Donetsk...

scrolly-chart.Header: Kyiv and surroundings lost in early April
scrolly-chart.Copy: After an initial rush on capital Kyiv fails, Russian forces retreat from north

scrolly-chart.Header: The grind produces fruits in east
scrolly-chart.Copy: Russia’s focus on east slowly works, with territory gains in Luhansk and Donetsk
Through most of summer 2022, an uneasy stalemate ensues with neither side able to break through the other
This changes in early September, when Ukrainian forces liberate the vast majority of Kharkiv oblast

scrolly-chart.Header: … and continues with Kherson city liberation
scrolly-chart.Copy: Two months later, Ukraine wins another key victory in liberating Kherson city. While Russia still controlled the majority of this oblast’s land, the regional capital was home to over a quarter of its pre-war population
